{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}} {{Multiple issues| {{Lead too short|date=May 2013}} {{BLP sources|date=May 2013}}}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Brad Wilk | image = Brad Wilk.jpg | caption = Brad Wilk performing at Optimus Alive '08 (July 10–12) in Lisbon, Portugal | image_size = | landscape = yes | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|9|5}} | birth_place = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S. | death_date = | instrument = {{flatlist| * Drums * percussion * vocals }} | genre = {{flatlist| * [[Alternative metal]] * [[rap metal]] * [[funk metal]] * [[alternative rock]] * [[hard rock]] * [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] * [[doom metal]] }} | occupation = {{flatlist| * Musician * songwriter }} | years_active = 1981–present | label = {{flatlist| * [[Epic Records|Epic]] * [[Interscope Records|Interscope]] }} | associated_acts = {{flatlist| * [[Rage Against the Machine]] * [[Audioslave]] * [[Puscifer]] * [[Greta (band)|Greta]] * [[Pearl Jam]] * [[Sound City Players]] * Indian Style * [[Black Sabbath]] * [[The Last Internationale]] * [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] * [[Juliette Lewis]] * [[Prophets of Rage]] }} | background = solo_singer }}
'''Bradley J. "Brad" Wilk''' (born September 5, 1968) is an American musician, actor, and activist. He is best known as the drummer of the rock bands [[Rage Against the Machine]] (1991–2000; 2007–2011), [[Audioslave]] (2001–2007; 2017), and [[Prophets of Rage]] (2016–present).
Wilk started his career as a drummer for [[Greta (band)|Greta]] in 1990, and helped co-found Rage with [[Tom Morello]] and [[Zack de la Rocha]] in August 1991. Following that band's breakup in October 2000 Wilk, Morello, Rage Against the Machine bassist [[Tim Commerford]], and [[Soundgarden]] front man [[Chris Cornell]] formed the [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] [[Audioslave]], which broke up in 2007. As of 2016, he is playing in the band [[Prophets of Rage]], with Commerford, Morello, [[Chuck D]], [[B-Real]] and [[DJ Lord]].
Wilk has also performed drums on English [[heavy metal music|metal]] band [[Black Sabbath]]'s final album ''[[13 (Black Sabbath album)|13]]''. The album was released in June 2013. Wilk briefly played with [[Pearl Jam]] shortly after the release of their debut album ''[[Ten (Pearl Jam album)|Ten]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Childers |first1=Chad |title=TOM MORELLO: 'IT'S A MIRACLE' RAGE AGAINST THE MACHINE MADE FOUR ALBUMS |url=http://loudwire.com/tom-morello-miracle-rage-against-the-machine-made-four-albums/ |website=[[Loudwire]] |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>
==Early life== Bradley J. Wilk was born on September 5, 1968, in [[Portland, Oregon]] and raised in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. His family later settled in [[Southern California]]. He started to play the drums when he was thirteen years old. He has cited [[John Bonham]], [[Keith Moon]], and [[Elvin Jones]] as his greatest influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drummersrepublic.com/drummers/ratm-drummer-brad-wilk-biography|title=Profile|publisher=Drummersrepublic.com|date=September 10, 2013|accessdate=2014-02-01|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129030420/http://www.drummersrepublic.com/drummers/ratm-drummer-brad-wilk-biography/|archivedate=November 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Wilk was a fan of [[Van Halen]] in his youth,<ref>{{cite web|title=Brad Wilk on Prophets of Rage, Sabbath and Alex Van Halen's swing|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/drums/brad-wilk-on-prophets-of-rage-sabbath-and-alex-van-halens-swing-646125|website=MusicRadar|language=en}}</ref> having seen the band live when he was thirteen.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}} He is of [[Jewish]]-[[Poles|Polish]] descent.
==Career== ===Rage Against the Machine=== Wilk's success as the drummer of [[Rage Against the Machine]] came from the failure of a different band; he once auditioned for a band called [[Lock Up (US band)|Lock Up]], who released one album (titled ''[[Something Bitchin' This Way Comes]]'') through Geffen records in 1989 and broke up when the album received little media attention upon release. Former Lock Up guitarist [[Tom Morello]] was looking to pick up where Lock Up left off and start a new band, and contacted Wilk, who was playing with the band [[Greta (band)|Greta]], to see if he was interested in playing the drums. A short while after, the duo met [[Zack de la Rocha]] while he was rapping freestyle in a club, and through him, bassist [[Tim Commerford]] (a childhood friend of de la Rocha). The band played two shows in 1991, and spent 1992 frequenting the L. A. club circuit, during which they signed a record deal with [[Epic Records]], and released their [[Rage Against the Machine (album)|self-titled debut album]] that November. They quickly achieved commercial success and would go on to release three more studio albums–''[[Evil Empire (album)|Evil Empire]]'' in 1996, ''[[The Battle of Los Angeles]]'' in 1999, and ''[[Renegades (Rage Against the Machine album)|Renegades]]'' in 2000– before disbanding in October 2000.
====Rage Against the Machine reunion==== Rage Against The Machine reunited to play at the [[Coachella Music Festival]] in [[Indio, California|Coachella]], California on January 22, 2007. On April 29, 2007, Rage Against The Machine reunited at the Coachella Music Festival (see [[Rage Against the Machine reunion tour]]). The band played in front of an EZLN backdrop to the largest crowds of the festival.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}} Initially thought to be a one-time event, the band played seven more shows that year in the United States (including their first non-festival concert in seven years at the [[Alpine Valley Music Theater]] in [[East Troy, Wisconsin|East Troy]], Wisconsin), and in January 2008, they played their first shows outside of the U.S. as part of the Big Day Out Festival in Australia and New Zealand.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} The band has since continued to tour around the world, headlining many large festivals in Europe and the United States, including Lollapalooza in Chicago. After a brief South America tour in 2010, they created their own festival, the L. A. Rising, which they headlined on July 30, 2011. This is their most recent show to date. In November 2012, they released an [[Rage Against the Machine (album)#XX 20th Anniversary Edition|XX anniversary boxset]] of their first album.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
===Audioslave=== {{Expand section|date=May 2013}} [[File:Brad Wilk Montreux Jazz Festival 2005.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Wilk performing with [[Audioslave]] at the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]] in 2005]] The remaining members formed [[Audioslave]] with former [[Soundgarden]] frontman [[Chris Cornell]]. The band released their [[Audioslave (album)|self-titled debut album]] in 2002, which was followed by ''[[Out of Exile]]'' in 2005, and ''[[Revelations (Audioslave album)|Revelations]]'' in 2006. Audioslave formally disbanded in February 2007 when Cornell left to focus on his solo career.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
===Prophets of Rage (2016-present)=== In 2016, Brad Wilk reunited with Tom Morello and Tim Commerford, and was joined by [[Chuck D]], [[B-Real]] and [[DJ Lord]] to form supergroup [[Prophets of Rage]]. They play covers from their [[Rage Against The Machine]], [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]] and [[Cypress Hill]] material, and new material as well. They're touring the United States under the statement "Make America Rage Again" to protest against [[Donald Trump]] policies and the [[2016 American presidential election]].
===Other projects=== Wilk and bandmate [[Tom Morello]] joined with [[Maynard James Keenan]] of [[Tool (band)|Tool]] and [[Billy Gould]] of [[Faith No More]]–in a lineup that was billed as Shandi's Addiction–to record the song "[[Calling Dr. Love]]" for the 1994 Kiss tribute album [[Kiss My Ass: Classic Kiss Regrooved]]. Wilk and bandmate Tim Commerford contributed in Keenan's side project [[Puscifer]] and his album ''[["V" Is for Vagina]]'' on the track "Momma Sed". Wilk also contributed drums to rap group [[Cypress Hill]]'s album ''[[Skull and Bones (album)|Skull and Bones]]''. In addition, Wilk composed the song "Snoop Bounce (Roc N Roll Remix)" for [[Snoop Dogg]]'s ''[[Death Row: Snoop Doggy Dogg at His Best|Death Row's Greatest Hits]]'' CD.
In 2005, Wilk played the lead role in the independent short movie [[Sleeping Dogs Lie (2005 film)|Sleeping Dogs Lie]] by writer Chumahan Bowen and director Stuart Lessner. The film also features [[Tool (band)|Tool]] lead singer [[Maynard James Keenan]] as Deputy Lance. Wilk played drums on [[Josh Homme]]'s tracks on the soundtrack to [[The Dangerous Lives of Altar Boys (soundtrack)|Dangerous Lives of Altar Boys]]. Wilk performed live with Tom Morello's side project, [[Street Sweeper Social Club]], at the 2010 Coachella music and arts festival. In 2013, Wilk and Commerford contributed drums and bass, respectively, for [[Dave Grohl]]'s ''[[Sound City (film)|Sound City]]'' soundtrack, on the song "Time Slowing Down". Wilk played several shows with the [[Sound City Players]].
Having established himself as a session musician, Wilk has also contributed drums on the [[Black Sabbath]] album ''[[13 (Black Sabbath album)|13]]'', which was released on June 11, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=184790|title=Black Sabbath: New Album Title Announced; Recording Drummer Revealed|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|date=January 12, 2012|accessdate=2012-01-12}}</ref> In late 2013, Wilk joined the band [[The Last Internationale]] and recently recorded their debut album called ''We Will Reign'' with producer Brendan O'Brien. The record was released on August 19, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5-GYMAFITbY|title=The Last Internationale - Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Indian Blood - YouTube|work=YouTube|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>
To the end of 2014 until June 2015, Brad Wilk was playing drums on tour with the [[Smashing Pumpkins]] along with [[Billy Corgan]], [[Jeff Schroeder]] and also [[Mark Stoermer]] on bass. On 26 February 2015, while touring Australia with the band, he joined the [[Foo Fighters]] on stage at Sydney's Olympic (ANZ) stadium playing drums for a [[Van Halen]] cover [[Ain't Talkin' 'bout Love]]. On August 3, 2015, Wilk sat-in with The 8G Band on ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=Michael|title=This Week's 'Late Night with Seth Meyers' Guests: Miles Teller; Craig Robinson; Jason Segel|url=http://tvimpulse.com/this-weeks-late-night-with-seth-meyers-guests-miles-teller-craig-robinson-jason-segel=44058|website=tvimpluse.com|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> He's also been drumming for [[Juliette Lewis]] on various tours and shows.
==Personal life== Wilk has noted a personal affinity with the number three throughout his life, and has positioned small decal stickers of the number "3" all over his drum kit, and as well as in the liner notes for [[Rage Against the Machine]]'s third album, ''[[The Battle of Los Angeles (album)|The Battle of Los Angeles]]''. In an interview with [[Modern Drummer]] Wilk said "Ever since I was eight or nine I've gravitated to the number three. It's something that has always been a really heavy number for me. It's tattooed on my arm, and I count in threes. Everyone in school was taught two, four, six, eight, ten- I'd count in threes in the way I'd walk, even in the decisions I'd make. It was all based on threes", and also incorporates 3 into his playing.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
Wilk was diagnosed with [[type 1 diabetes]] in 1997, and is active in raising money for diabetes awareness.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sistrunk|first=Jeff|url=http://forecast.diabetes.org/magazine/features/rock-drummer-brad-wilk-type-1-and-touring|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709200845/http://forecast.diabetes.org/magazine/features/rock-drummer-brad-wilk-type-1-and-touring|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2012-07-09|title=Rock Drummer Brad Wilk on Type 1 and Touring &#124; Diabetes Forecast Magazine|publisher=Forecast.diabetes.org|accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref> He has donated about $12,000 to the Orange County chapter of the [[Juvenile Diabetes Research Foundation]] (JDRF).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dlife.com/diabetes/famous_people/musicians/brad-wilk-biography|title=Brad Wilk Biography|publisher=dLife|date=November 28, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306111236/http://www.dlife.com/diabetes/famous_people/musicians/brad-wilk-biography|archivedate=March 6, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
Unable to find an all natural, sugar-free lemonade that would fit with his diet management and exercise plan, Wilk began formulating his own lemonade in his kitchen, using [[stevia]] in the place of sugar. After receiving positive feedback from friends and family, Wilk launched ''Olade''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsupplywarehouse.com/finelineDisplay.php?id=383170 |title=ASW – Olade Juice Beverages |publisher=Artsupplywarehouse.com |date=April 17, 2008 |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref> Since December 2009, the [[Food and Drug Administration]] has approved Olade to be put into the market as a non-dietary supplement, meaning anyone with or without diabetes can consume it.
