{{Infobox writer | name = Dorothy, Lady Pakington | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Lady Pakington, née Dorothy Coventry (1623-1679) by Cornelis Jonson van Ceulen (1593-1661).jpg | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = painting by [[Cornelis Janssens van Ceulen]] | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Dorothy Coventry | birth_date = 1623 | birth_place = in or near [[London]], England | death_date = 10 May 1679 | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = writer | language = English | residence = | nationality = English | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = religious works | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = [[Sir John Pakington, 2nd Baronet]] | partner = | children = | relatives = [[Thomas Coventry, 1st Baron Coventry|Sir Thomas Coventry]] (father) | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} --> | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} '''Dorothy, Lady Pakington''' (1623 – 10 May 1679) was an [[England|English]] friend and supporter of learned clergymen, and a writer of religious works. She was for many years reputed to be the author of ''[[The Whole Duty of Man]]''. She enjoyed the esteem and friendship of the most eminent divines of her time. Dr. [[Henry Hammond]] resided at her home for several years.{{sfn|Williams (called Ysgafell.)|1861|p=116-17}}
==Early years== Dorothy Coventry was born in or near [[London]] about the middle of the reign of [[James I]].{{sfn|Craik|1847|p=68}} She was the daughter of [[Thomas Coventry, 1st Baron Coventry|Sir Thomas Coventry]], the [[Lord Keeper of the Great Seal|Lord Keeper]],{{sfn|Williams (called Ysgafell.)|1861|p=116-17}} and his second wife, Elizabeth (1583–1653), daughter of John Aldersey of Spurstow, Cheshire, and widow of William Pitchford.
==Career== She married [[Sir John Pakington, 2nd Baronet]] (1621–1680), of Westwood, Worcestershire. The couple had at least three surviving children: one son and two daughters.{{sfn|Virtue and Company|1875|p=270}}
A fervent royalist, Dorothy Pakington wrote manuscript prayers, and shared in the circulation of religious and philosophical manuscripts in the group of clergymen around the king's chaplain, [[Henry Hammond]]. The extent of her reputation is shown by the fact that contemporaries believed her the author of ''[[The Whole Duty of Man]]''. Although [[George Ballard (biographer)|George Ballard]] defended this attribution, modern scholars instead follow two nineteenth-century writers — [[Richard Harris Barham|Richard Barham]] and [[C. E. Doble]] — who attributed the work to Hammond's friend [[Richard Allestree]]. She led a retired life, and devoted herself to learning, piety, and good works. She was the author of several religious books: ''The Gentleman’s Calling'', ''The Lady’s Calling'', ''The Government of the Tongue'', ''The Christian’s Birthright'', and ''The Causes of the Decay of Christian Piety''.{{sfn|Williams (called Ysgafell.)|1861|p=116-17}}
Pakington died 10 May 1679.{{sfn|Williams (called Ysgafell.)|1861|p=116-17}}
